# Making Your Classroom More Accessible

#### This level includes several strategies for making your classroom more accessible. Don't feel overwhelmed by the amount you read here - instead, while you read, commit to choosing **one or two** strategies to implement in the **next month**. You can always come back to this page to pick new strategies to implement.

## Universal Design for Learning

#### **Universal Design for Learning (UDL)** is "a framework to improve and optimize teaching and learning for all people based on scientific insights into how humans learn" <a href="https://www.cast.org/impact/universal-design-for-learning-udl" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">(CAST)</a>. UDL provides guidance for how to provide students with **multiple means of engagement, representation, and action & expression**.

#### The University of Florida’s Creative Technology Research Lab (CTRL) has adapted the UDL guidelines for computer science (UDL4CS) to provide teachers with the tools to make learning more accessible for their students. This is a great resource for K-12 computer science educators. 

### **Read About the UDL Guidelines**

#### There are two ways to read the UDL for CS guidelines:

* #### Review the <a href="https://ctrl.education.ufl.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2020/05/Copy-of-UDL-and-CS_CT-remix.pdf" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">UDL4CS Guidelines in text format</a>
* #### Review videos provided in the <a href="https://udl4cs.education.ufl.edu/interactive-table/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="blank">UDL4CS Interactive Table</a>

### **Watch a Video About the UDL Guidelines**

#### Would you like another way of engaging with Universal Design for Learning methods? Check out this video by the DO-IT (Disabilities, Opportunities, Internetworking, and Technology) Center at the University of Washington about including students with disabilities in computing courses.

##### **Note**: This video opens in a new tab.

