## Improving Your Physical Space

<img src="https://images.code.org/549644e1c7f38e946420664d30b84477-image-1736057061352.04.19 PM.png" alt="A group of students and their teacher in a computer science classroom." style="border-radius:20px; float: right; height: 200px; clear: both; margin: 20px 20px 0px 20px;">

#### **AccessCSForAll**, from the University of Washington, provides guidelines for how to make a computer lab accessible for students with a range of disabilities. While this resource has been created for educators who teach at the university level, many of the guidelines are universal and may benefit your classroom design.

* ### Review <a href="https://www.washington.edu/accesscomputing/equal-access-universal-design-computer-labs" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="blank">Equal Access: Universal Design of Computer Labs</a>

#### The above document includes a lot of valuable information. If you feel overwhelmed, consider starting with just the following questions, from the same document:

* #### Are printed materials within easy reach from a variety of heights and without furniture blocking access?
* #### Do video presentations have captions? Audio descriptions?
* #### Are adequate work areas available for both right- and left-handed users?
* #### Are key documents provided in language(s) other than English?
* #### Is a trackball available for those who have difficulty controlling a mouse?
* #### Can controls on computers, printers, scanners, and other devices be reached from a seated position?
